  "design_rationale": "This design optimizes for execution time on TPC-H analytical queries with heavy emphasis on the lineitem fact table (6M rows, accessed by all queries). Key decisions: (1) Sort lineitem by l_shipdate to enable zone map block skipping for all queries (Q1: <=, Q3: >, Q6: range). (2) Zone maps on l_shipdate, l_discount, l_quantity for multi-predicate pruning in Q6 (skip 86%+ of blocks). (3) Dictionary encoding for all low-cardinality columns (l_returnflag, l_linestatus, c_mktsegment, o_orderstatus, p_brand, etc.) reduces storage and enables fast integer comparisons. (4) Hash indexes on all PK/FK columns for O(1) join probes. (5) Binary columnar storage with mmap enables zero-copy access and massive column pruning (Q6: 75% I/O savings). (6) Block size of 100K rows balances zone map granularity vs metadata overhead (~60 blocks for lineitem, ~15 for orders). (7) Parallel ingestion exploits 64 cores: concurrent table loads + chunked parsing for large tables. (8) HDD storage compensated by aggressive block skipping and sequential I/O patterns from sorted data. Expected performance: Q1 100-500ms, Q3 1-3s, Q6 50-200ms with 8-16 thread parallelism.",
  "summary": "Binary columnar storage with lineitem sorted by l_shipdate. Zone maps on shipdate/discount/quantity enable aggressive block skipping (86%+ for Q6). Dictionary encoding for low-cardinality categoricals. Hash indexes on all join keys. Parallel ingestion across 64 cores. Column pruning saves 50-75% I/O. Expected 10-50x speedup vs naive row-based execution."
